Docker Container Recovery Quick Notes :

1. Check whether Docker Engine / Docker Desktop is running on the VM.

If Docker is stopped, open Docker Desktop and start it.
Sometimes simply opening Docker Desktop will start the Docker Engine automatically.




2. Check container status:

   *  docker ps -a

   If the container exists but is in Exited state, start it:

   docker start <container-name>

   Example:

   *  docker start sarab-container




3. Verify the container is running:

   *   docker ps



4. If needed, access the running container:

   *  docker exec -it <container-name> sh




5. To prevent containers from staying stopped after Docker Engine restarts, configure a restart policy:

   *   docker update --restart unless-stopped <container-name>

   Example:

   *   docker update --restart unless-stopped sarab-container

   Other options:

   always
   unless-stopped
   on-failure

This issue commonly occurs after Docker Desktop, Docker Engine, WSL, or the VM is restarted. The container still exists but needs to be started again unless a restart policy is configured.


